<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900629-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>900629-0015.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>06/29/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   JAPAN AND THE U.S. completed a broad accord designed toreduce their trade imbalance. Japan promised to spend more onpublic works, toughen antitrust policies and streamline itsdistribution system. The U.S. pledged to balance its budget,improve worker training and boost research spending. The pactgot a cool reaction from some legislators, economists andbusiness people.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Polaroid is letting Minolta sell a Polaroid instant camerato U.S. customers under a Minolta brand name. The highlyunusual marketing move reflects Polaroid's sluggish sales.   ---   Crude oil inventories are at an eight-year high, raisingthe prospect of tumbling petroleum prices if OPEC doesn'trein in production soon. Persian Gulf producers have beencutting their third-quarter contract prices.   ---   Budget negotiators are talking increasingly about raisingtaxes on Social Security benefits or reducing the program'scost-of-living raises.   ---   The earnings outlook for the second quarter is largelypositive, despite some recent negative surprises, analystsand money managers say. This is good news for investors withbroadly diversified stock portfolios.   ---   Lotus's copyright on the 1-2-3 program was infringed byPaperback Software International in its VP Planner, a federaljudge ruled. The decision could foreshadow similar verdictsin other software disputes.   ---   Apple Computer has dropped plans for an initial publicoffering by its Claris software unit and intends to fold thebusiness back into the parent firm, industry executives say.   ---   A Mobil affiliate won clearance from the Nigeriangovernment to proceed with the $1 billion development of arich offshore petroleum field.   ---   Bond prices rose as investors reacted to brisk demand forthe latest Treasury note offering. The stock market alsogained, boosting the Dow Jones Industrial Average 16.58points to 2878.71. The dollar was mixed.   ---   Venezuela reached an agreement with its major bankcreditors that includes provisions for new loans and forcutting back old credits and the interest payments due onthem.   ---   Pathe's $1.31 billion bid to buy MGM/UA appeared injeopardy after Pathe said it reached an impasse with TimeWarner over financing. Pathe said it will seek other sourcesof funding, and continue talking to Time.   ---   Manufacturers Hanover plans to take a substantialsecond-quarter charge linked to its cost-cutting plan. Thebanking concern also is placing more than $150 million ofloans to Trump on nonperforming status.   ---   ATandamp;T will cut long-distance prices an average of 2.2%, ormore than $300 million a year, starting Sunday.   ---   Soybean planting covered 58 million acres this year, thegovernment estimated, cutting its previous figure by 1.4million acres. Some analysts expect soybean prices to climbtoday.   ---   A group of insurers is developing a computer network toimprove communications with independent agents. Critics areskeptical about the system's benefit to consumers.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 136,120,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2878.71, up 16.58; transportation 1142.70, up 1.82; utilities208.63, unchanged.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3438.13, up14.09.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.81, up 0.64; spotindex 131.81, up 0.43.   Dollar: 153.15 yen, off 1.30; 1.6730 marks, up 0.0085.</TEXT></DOC>